    Why is Delhi famous?
    New Delhi is best known as the location of India's national government. New Delhi has great historical significance as it was home to powerful people, such as the Pāṇḍavas and the Mughals. The city has many historical monuments and tourist attractions as well as lively marketplaces and great food, such as chaat.

    Why is Delhi called New Delhi?
    Its construction was done in 1911 during British rule, and it was named New Delhi due to its contrasted architectural style when compared to the older parts of Delhi. It developed from the older Raisina Hill area and is part of the larger National Capital Territory (NCT) of Delhi.

    About

    Description

    Delhi, India’s capital territory, is a massive metropolitan area in the country’s north. In Old Delhi, a neighborhood dating to the 1600s, stands the imposing Mughal-era Red Fort, a symbol of India, and the sprawling Jama Masjid mosque, whose courtyard accommodates 25,000 people. Nearby is Chandni Chowk, a vibrant bazaar filled with food carts, sweets shops and spice stalls. ― Google
    Area: 1,483 km²
    Area code: +91 11
    Capital, Delhi Sultanate: 1214
    Capital, Mughal Empire: 1526, intermittently with Agra
    Elevation: 200–250 m (650–820 ft)
    HDI (2018): 0.839 (Very High) · 1st
    ISO 3166 code: IN-DL
